text: 4. Description of the Proposed Action
label: HH1

text: The action requested in this notification is to allow the safe use of a rubber-modified polysty-
label: BODY

text: rene copolymer as a component of food-contact articles, for all food types. This rubber-modi-
label: BODY

text: fied polystyrene copolymer is comparable to polymers described in 21 CFR ยง177.1810
label: BODY

text: (3)(b)(l .i) but differs with respect to the Tgl due to the random PSB - mid-block.
label: H4

text: More specifically, the polymer, which is the subject of this notification is a rubber-modified
label: BODY

text: polystyrene resin prepared by the polymerization of 1,3-butadiene and styrene such that the
label: BODY

text: resulting product contains between 60 to 75 % by weight of polymer units derived from styrene
label: BODY

text: monomer. The rubber-modified polystyrene copolymer is referred to herein-after as:
label: BODY

text: Styroflex@.
label: BODY

text: Styroflex@ is composed of two polystyrene block end caps, and a randomized copolybutadi-
label: BODY

text: enektyrene mid-block. The random block functions by improving the elongation properties of
label: BODY

text: the polymer, thus conveying high elasticity to the finished article. Accordingly, the polymer is
label: BODY

text: expected to be employed primarily in the production of food-contact articles that require the
label: BODY

text: clarity of general-purpose polystyrene and an improved the elasticity. Articles that may be
label: BODY

text: prepared with the use of the polymer include such items as films or coatings for food-contact
label: BODY

text: use. Styroflex@ is expected to compete in these applications primarily with high impact polysty-
label: BODY

text: rene (HIPS), where a high elasticity is required, and to a degree with plasticized PVC cling
label: BODY

text: films. While Styroflex@ exhibits a desirable combination of elasticity and clarity, it is essentially

text: The polymer will be manufactured by the Notifier at its production facilities located in Ludwigs-
label: BODY

text: hafen (Germany), Antwerp (Belgium), and Altamira (Mexico). The Notifier does not manufac-
label: BODY

text: ture finished food-contact articles containing the resin; rather, it will sell resin to compounders
label: BODY

text: or to processors that are involved in the manufacture of food-contact articles. Thus, the co-
label: BODY

text: polymer is expected to be used by film producers at a number of different production sites
label: BODY

text: throughout the United States. Food-contact materials containing Styroflex@ will be used in
label: BODY

text: patterns corresponding to national population density, and will be widely distributed across the
label: BODY

text: country. Consequently, it is expected that disposal will occur nationwide, with about 20% of
label: BODY

text: the materials ultimately being incinerated, according to current Environmental Protection
label: BODY

text: Agency (EPA) projections, and with 80% being disposed of by means of sanitary landfill or, to
label: BODY

text: some extent, by recycling.

label: HH1

text: To summarize the information provided in Section A, the subject polymer is produced by the
label: BODY

text: reaction of a mixture of styrene and 1,3 butadiene. The reaction is carried out by polymeriza-
label: BODY

text: tion of the monomers dissolved in a hydrocarbon solvent. The polymer consists of two poly-
label: BODY

text: styrene end blocks and a randomized copolybutadiene styrene middle block. The polymer
label: BODY

text: contains a mixture of stabilizers that are cleared for use in all polymers.
label: BODY

text: We have determined that no extraordinary circumstances apply to the manufacture of the
label: BODY

text: food-contact substance. Therefore, information regarding production of the food-contact sub-
label: BODY

text: stance is not provided.
label: BODY

text: Disposal by the ultimate consumer of food packaging materials containing StyroflexB will be
label: BODY

text: by conventional rubbish disposal and, hence, by sanitary landfill or incineration.
label: BODY

text: The rubber-modified polystyrene copolymer is prepared from only carbon and hydrogen con-
label: BODY

text: taining materials. Thus, no toxic combustion products are expected as a result of the incinera-
label: BODY

text: tion of this product in a properly operated incinerator.

text: 7. Fate of Emitted Substances in the Environment
label: HH1

text: (a) Air
label: BODY

text: No significant effect on the concentrations and exposures to any substances in the atmos-
label: BODY

text: phere are anticipated due to the proposed use of Styroflex@.
label: BODY

text: The manufacture of Styroflex@ generates as waste stream activated carbon charged with in-
label: BODY

text: organic and organic compounds. This waste stream is sent to a licensed industrial waste
label: BODY

text: treatment facility for incineration. Consequently, no significant volatile emissions are antici-
label: BODY

text: pated at the site of production of the rubber-modified polystyrene copolymer.
label: BODY

text: Moreover, the polymer per se is of high molecular weight and does not volatilize. As discussed
label: BODY

text: in Item 5 above, residual monomer levels are extremely low. Finally, the products of complete
label: BODY

text: combustion of the polymer are carbon dioxide and water; the concentrations of these sub-
label: BODY

text: stances in the environment would not be significantly altered by the proper incineration of the
label: BODY

text: polymer in the amounts utilized for food packaging applications.
label: BODY

text: (b) Water
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: of the environment at levels that could cause any adverse environmental impact. More specifi-

text: 8. Environmental Effects of Released .Substances
label: HH1

text: As discussed previously, substances that may be released to the environment upon the use
label: BODY

text: and disposal of food packaging materials containing include minute levels of oligomeric spe-
label: BODY

text: cies and/or stabilizers from the landfilling of materials containing the additive, and small quan-
label: BODY

text: tities of carbon dioxide and water from its incineration. No constituents of the copolymer may
label: BODY

text: reasonably be expected to leach at more than trace levels from finished packaging materials
label: BODY

text: placed in landfill sites.
label: BODY

text: Since the substance is not expected to leach significantly from finished packaging materials

text: 9. Use of Resources and Energy
label: HH1

text: As is the case with other food-packaging materials, the production, use and disposal of
label: BODY

text: Styroflex@ involves the use of natural resources such as petroleum products, coal, and the
label: BODY

text: like. However, the manufacture of the subject polymer will not result in an increase in the use
label: BODY

text: of such natural resources since the product is intended to compete with and replace HIPS
label: BODY

text: other rubber-modified polystyrene copolymers currently on the market for use in food pack-
label: BODY

text: aging applications, which require the expenditure of the same or similar quantities of re-
label: BODY

text: sources to produce. Furthermore, the use of the subject resin in food-contact articles will not
label: BODY

text: significantly alter the applications for which such articles are suitable.
label: BODY

text: The use of Styroflex@ is also not expected to have any impact on current or future recycling
label: BODY

text: efforts. The polymer is expected to be used primarily or solely in food packaging applications
label: BODY

text: that currently employ styrene-based polymers, including such articles as meat trays, egg car-
label: BODY

text: tons, and food packaging film. To the extent that currently cleared rubber-modified polystyrene
label: BODY

text: is recycled after consumer use, is equally recyclable with this material since the polymers are
label: BODY

text: identical with the exception of a slight difference in comonomer ratios. Moreover, is not ex-
label: BODY

text: pected to compete with non-styrene based polymers or other materials in applications in which
label: BODY

text: the currently used materials are widely recycled. For example, the subject polymer is not ex-
label: BODY

text: pected to replace glass bottles or jars, aluminum cans, polyethylene terephthalate (PET) bot-
label: BODY

text: tles for carbonated beverages, or high-density polyethylene milk jugs.

text: 10. Mitigation Measures
label: BODY

text: As shown above, no significant effects on the environment are anticipated from the use and
label: BODY

text: disposal of articles containing the subject polymer. This is primarily due to the low toxicity of
label: BODY

text: the polymer and the low levels of migration of polymer constituents as shown in Section B of
label: BODY

text: the notification, as well as the close similarity between Styroflex@ and the currently cleared sty-
label: BODY

text: rene-based polymers with which it is intended to compete. Thus, the use of the FCS as pro-
label: BODY

text: posed is not reasonably expected to result in any new environmental problem requiring miti-
label: BODY

text: gation measures of any kind.
label: BODY

text: 11. Alternatives to the Proposed Action
label: BODY

text: No potential adverse environmental effects are identified herein which would necessitate al-
label: BODY

text: ternative actions to that proposed in this notification. The alternative of not approving the ac-
label: BODY

text: tion proposed herein would simply result in the continued use of currently cleared HIPS poly-
label: BODY

text: mers; such action would have no environmental impact. However, in view of the excellent
label: BODY

text: qualities of the Styroflex@ for food packaging, the fact that resin components are not expected
label: BODY

text: to migrate in more than minuscule amounts from finished food packaging materials into food
label: BODY

text: or into land in which such containers are disposed, and the absence of any significant envi-
label: BODY

text: ronmental impact which would result from its use, allowing this notification to become effective
label: BODY

text: to permit the safe use of Styroflex@ as a component of articles intended for use in contact with
label: BODY

text: food is environmentally safe in every respect.
